a union representing 41000 telephone workers at bell atlantic 
walked off the job sunday morning joining counterparts at nynex 
corp and pacific telesis who had begun a strike hours earlier 
union and company spokesmen said 
mary ohara district coordinator in philadelphia for the 
communications workers of america said talks with bell atlantic 
broke up around 645 am and pickets were being set up 
bell atlantic based in philadelphia is parent to local phone 
companies in delaware the district of columbia maryland new 
jersey pennsylvania virginia and west virginia 
talks continued sunday morning between another union the 
international brotherhood of electrical workers and the bell 
atlantic subsidiaries in pennsylvania and new jersey said tom 
duddy a spokesman for bell of pennsylvania that union represents 
11000 operators and clerical workers at the two subsidiaries 
hours earlier more than 100000 cwa and ibew workers walked out 
at new yorkbased nynex and san franciscobased pacific telesis 
a tentative agreement was reached between the cwa and a fourth 
regional telephone company atlantabased bellsouth which employs 
64000 union workers and provides phone service in nine states in 
the southeast 
officials have said that most directdial telephone calls would 
not be affected by phone company walkouts because they are handled 
by automated equipment but customers could expect delays in 
directory assistance calls operatorassisted calls and in service 
and installation jobs 
in all 221000 telecommunications workers were covered by the 
talks to replace contracts that expired at 1159 pm saturday the 
four companies provide service to 24 states and the nations 
capital 
the regional telephone companies nicknamed baby bells were 
created by the 1984 breakup of american telephone amp telegraph 
contracts with three of the other baby bells ameritech us 
west and southwestern bell expire next saturday those three 
companies employ 131000 union workers and provide phone service in 
24 states 
the unions announced the strike against new yorkbased nynex 
well before the 1159 edt deadline saying myriad differences 
remained so great were the differences that no formal talks were 
held saturday 
nynex serves seven northeast states new york massachusetts 
rhode island maine new hampshire vermont and parts of 
connecticut cwa represents 40000 nynex workers ibew 20000 
talks with pacific telesis based in san francisco were held 
throughout the day but the unions announced the strike there at 
midnight 3 am edt 
pacific telesis is parent company of californias pacific bell 
co and nevada bell telephone co cwa represents 42000 pacific 
telesis workers ibew 2500 
