<TEXT>
americans are spending a smaller share of 
their incomes on food than ever before the agriculture department 
says 
according to the departments food cost review americans 
overall spent 411 billion on food in 1988 118 percent of their 
total disposable personal income 
that is down from 13 percent five years earlier and 135 percent 
in 1978 the departments economic research service says when the 
government began keeping statistics in 1929 nearly 25 percent of 
disposable personal income was spent on food 
that percentage has declined steadily over the years except for 
the 1970s when there was relatively high food price inflation the 
department says 
citing a 1986 survey by the us department of labor the 
agriculture department noted that the percentage of income spent on 
food varies by size and income of family 
aftertax income spent for food varied from 127 percent for 
households with incomes of 3000039000 to 274 percent for 
families with incomes of 50009999 
although much has been said about the growing number of meals 
taken at restaurants and fastfood establishments the share of 
disposable income on food eaten away from home has risen only 
gradually from 32 percent in 1929 to 45 percent in 1988 
expenseaccount meals are excluded 
the agriculture department excludes pet food ice and prepared 
feeds and deducts more for nonfood items such as drugs and 
household supplies in arriving at the food component of grocery 
bills 
the declining percentage of food expenditures in relation to 
rising income was noted by 19th century economist ernest engel the 
report says 
a decline in this percentage reflects a highly developed 
economy in which there is money to spend on personal services and 
other discretionary items the report says some of these 
additional services ordinarily are purchases along with food this 
reasoning largely explains the slight increase in the percentage of 
income spent on food away from home 
so how did farmers make out 
of the 411 billion spent on food 395 billion was spent on 
food produced on american farms the rest was spent on imported 
food and fishery products 
the 395 billion represents a 5 percent increase over the 
previous year and is a record dollar amount spent by consumers on 
food produced in america 
meat products accounted for 29 percent of total expenditures 
followed by 22 percent for fruits and vegetables 
</TEXT>
